Dragon Fruit

Exotic, vibrant, and packed with antioxidants. Explore the varieties, health benefits, and culinary secrets of the cactus fruit that blooms under the moon.

A Spectrum of Sweetness

Not all dragon fruits are created equal. From the common white-fleshed to the rare, super-sweet yellow, discover the unique profiles of each variety.

White Fleshed

Hylocereus undatus

Red Fleshed

Hylocereus costaricensis

Yellow Skin

Hylocereus megalanthus

The Classic White

The most common variety found in supermarkets. It features striking pink skin with green scales and a white flesh speckled with edible black seeds. The flavor is mild and subtle, often compared to a kiwi or pear but less acidic.

Acidity
psychiatry

Best for: Salads, garnishes, and those who prefer mild flavors.

Nutritional Powerhouse

Don't let the mild taste fool you. Dragon fruit is dense with nutrients, low in calories, and a fantastic source of antioxidants, especially the red-fleshed varieties which contain betacyanins.

In The Kitchen

The Half Cut

Place the dragon fruit on a stable cutting board. Using a sharp chef's knife, slice the fruit lengthwise directly through the center, from stem to bottom.

restaurant Chef's Tip: Look for bright, even skin without too many shriveled spots.

Tropical Smoothie Bowl

5 mins Breakfast

A vibrant, Instagram-worthy breakfast packed with nutrients. Uses frozen dragonfruit for a thick, sorbet-like texture.

grocery Ingredients

  • 1 pack frozen dragon fruit (or 1 cup fresh, frozen)
  • 1 frozen banana
  • cup frozen mango chunks
  • cup coconut milk

1. Add frozen dragon fruit, banana, mango, and coconut milk to a high-speed blender.

2. Blend on high until smooth and creamy. Use a tamper if needed to push fruit down.

3. Pour into a bowl and top with granola, chia seeds, and fresh fruit slices.

4. Serve immediately while cold and thick!

Zesty Dragon Salsa

10 mins Appetizer

A refreshing, crunchy, and sweet-savory twist on classic salsa. Perfect with fish tacos or tortilla chips.

grocery Ingredients

  • 1 white or red dragon fruit, cubed
  • cup red onion, finely diced
  • cup fresh cilantro, chopped
  • 1 lime, juiced
  • Salt & jalapeno (optional)

1. Cut the dragon fruit in half, scoop out flesh, and cut into small uniform cubes.

2. In a medium bowl, combine dragon fruit, red onion, and cilantro.

3. Squeeze fresh lime juice over the mixture and sprinkle with a pinch of salt.

4. Toss gently to combine. Let sit for 10 minutes for flavors to meld before serving.

light_mode Did you know?

The Queen of the Night

The dragon fruit cactus (Hylocereus) is a night-blooming plant. Its massive, fragrant white flowers open only once, appearing in the evening and wilting by morning. They are often pollinated by bats and moths under the moonlight.
